<biogHist>
<abstract>Legal supervision was introduced by the <span style="font-style:italic">Child Welfare Act</span> 1960. It provided for children who were neglected or had committed an offence to be supervised by a Child Welfare Officer for up to three years. During this period, the child received support and advice. The child had to obey the 'reasonable directions' of the Officer. Legal supervision was sometimes abbreviated to 'Sup.' and referred to on government records in the abbreviated form.</abstract>

</biogHist>
